h a product mix of furniture and appliances) directed at credit sales to consumers in the LSM3-5 category\'92.  }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs20\lang1033\loch\f4\fs20\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs20\lang1033\loch\f4\fs20\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 The merging parties contended in the present dispute that the same market definition should not be adopted but that the relevant market was composed of all furniture and appliance retailers aggregated together into a national geographic market.  The Tribun
al did not make a definitive finding in relation to the applicable market.  It did suggest that unlike the Ellerines merger, the merging firms in the present dispute also had a \'91strong footprint\'92 in the mass discount market.  The Tribunal found that the in
dependents did not act as a counterveiling power to the market behaviour of the chains and their plurality notwithstanding, they should be excluded from any relevant market determination.  On this basis and employing the relevant 3-5 LSM category the Tribu
nal concluded \'91The merged firms have 24,2% of the post merger market.  The HHI (Herfindahl \'96 Hirschman Index of market concentration) is 2113 pre-merger and 2380 post merger, yielding a change in HHI of 267, suggestive of a concentrated market\'92. Viewed acc
ordingly, the Tribunal came to the conclusion \'91that it is probable that this concentration would have occurred even absent the merger\'92.  }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs20\lang1033\loch\f4\fs20\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs20\lang1033\loch\f4\fs20\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 The Tribunal then engaged in an enquiry mandated by section 12 A of the Competition Act 89 of 1998 (\'91the Act\'92), in terms of which the Tribunal is required to determine \'91whether or not the merger is likely to substantially prevent or lessen competition\'92.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs20\lang1033\loch\f4\fs20\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\sl480\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs20\lang1033\loch\f4\fs20\lang1033{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0{\ltrch\dbch The parties had argued that Profurn was a failing firm and hence contended that the \'91concentration is not the cause of the creation or strengthening of a dominant position which has a significant impact on the competitive situation on the relevant market\'92.
  See }}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0{\ltrch\dbch\hich\b\loch\b France v the European Community Commission }{\ltrch\dbch[1998] ECR 1-1375.}}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\sl480\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs20\lang1033\loch\f4\fs20\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 The Tribunal held that, although not all the elements of the failing firm doctrine had been established, \'91we are persuaded by the evidence that certain businesses of Profurn would have exited the market if there had either not been a merger, or if another 
firm with a less competitively adverse profile had been the purchaser\'92.  The Tribunal concluded that, although the merger would have increased concentration and therefore reduced competition in the market (however so defined), this development would have o
ccurred, absent the merger, and accordingly the merger could not be held to be the cause of the defect of the present state of the market. Having made no adverse finding against the parties in respect of the horizontal aspects of the merger, the Tribunal t
urned to the vertical effects thereof.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs20\lang1033\loch\f4\fs20\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs20\lang1033\loch\f4\fs20\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 The key issue with regard to vertical effects concerned the role of Steinhoff, the country\'92s largest furniture manufacturer.  According to the Tribunal, it was common cause that Steinhoff was the dominant firm in manufacturing of furniture as well as in th
e bedding industry.  It cited figures provided by the independent firms to the effect that Steinhoff enjoyed 54% of this market.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs20\lang1033\loch\f4\fs20\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs20\lang1033\loch\f4\fs20\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 The Tribunal then engaged in an analysis of the evidence, the key conclusions of which were:}
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-720\f4\lang1033\f4\fs24\f4\fs20\lang1025\sl480\slmult1\qj 1.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\sl480\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-720\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 Steinhoff was the dominant supplier of bedding and furniture in the South African retail market.}
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-720\f4\lang1033\f4\fs24\f4\fs20\lang1025\sl480\slmult1\qj 2.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\sl480\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-720\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 It enjoyed particularly close relationships with at least two of the key chains being the JD Group as well as Relyant.}
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-720\f4\lang1033\f4\fs24\f4\fs20\lang1025\sl480\slmult1\qj 3.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\sl480\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-720\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 It had over the past decade grown dramatically due to a series of acquisitions while at the same time the role of independent manufacturers had declined markedly.}
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-720\f4\lang1033\f4\fs24\f4\fs20\lang1025\sl480\slmult1\qj 4.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\sl480\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-720\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 Retailers had fewer manufacturers to procure core product, thereby inhibiting their ability to secure best prices and product choices.}
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-720\f4\lang1033\f4\fs24\f4\fs20\lang1025\sl480\slmult1\qj 5.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\sl480\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-720\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 Independent manufacturers were dependent for their survival on preserving the custom of the chains in order to achieve some economies of scale and therefore retain their competitiveness.}
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-720\f4\lang1033\f4\fs24\f4\fs20\lang1025\sl480\slmult1\qj 6.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\sl480\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-720\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 The chains needed to secure high volumes of product and could only so achieve this at best prices by securing rebates from Steinhoff.}
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-720\f4\lang1033\f4\fs24\f4\fs20\lang1025\sl480\slmult1\qj 7.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\sl480\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-720\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 Profurn was identified by the independents as being one of the chains that had \'91championed the cause of independent manufacturers\'92.}
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-720\f4\lang1033\f4\fs24\f4\fs20\lang1025\sl480\slmult1\qj 8.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\sl480\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-720\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 Of all the chains, JD had the closest relationship to Steinhoff.}
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-720\f4\lang1033\f4\fs24\f4\fs20\lang1025\sl480\slmult1\qj 9.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\sl480\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-720\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 Within the merged group it was likely that JD would alter Profurn\'92s purchasing powers in favour of Steinhoff and to the detriment of the independents. This would lead to a further reduction in the role of the independents and consequently increase concentr
ation in the manufacturing sector.}
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-720\f4\lang1033\f4\fs24\f4\fs20\lang1025\sl480\slmult1\qj 10.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\sl480\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls2\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-720\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 The demise of the independent manufacturing sector was likely to raise barriers to entry to the increasingly concentrated retail sector.  }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\sl480\slmult1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 
