 2002 from the Competition Commission in which it was calculated that the share of Steinhoff was in the region of 24.4% for the market for local furniture comprising case goods, bedding and upholstery.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs20\lang1033\loch\f4\fs20\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af4\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs20\lang1033\loch\f4\fs20\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 Mr Subel also referred to the cross-examination of Mr Pritchard, and in particular the latter\'92s  evidence  regarding Steinhoff\'92s  54% market share. When cross-examined by Mr Pretorius on behalf of Profurn, Mr Pritchard had no satisfactory answer to the pro
position that Steinhoff\'92s market share was closer to 20% than the 54% which he had informed the Tribunal.  Mr Subel submitted that, as there was no satisfactory explanation from Mr Pritchard or any of the other witnesses, the Tribunal\'92s conclusion that \'91St
